text_trans: Nuclear contaminated water is not nuclear wastewater. Nuclear power plants all produce nuclear wastewater. After strict treatment and testing， nuclear wastewater can be discharged into the ocean without causing any impact on the environment or humans. However， Japan discharges nuclear contaminated water， with a staggering total of approximately 1.34 million tons of Fukushima nuclear contaminated water. The Japanese government will discharge approximately 3.12 million tons of nuclear contaminated water into the sea four times in 2023 for at least 30 years

Qinshan's second cooling water system is used to cool the first cooling water to maintain the thermal balance of the entire nuclear power plant. text_trans: Japan's discharge is not nuclear wastewater， but rather nuclear wastewater. The concept of cooling water that has passed through the core of a nuclear reactor and cooling water that has not passed through the core are different. The former is called primary cooling water， while the latter is called secondary cooling water. Although it has not passed through the core， secondary cooling water also contains trace amounts of radioactivity. The main radioactive element is tritium， which can be directly discharged into the sea as long as it meets the safety standards of the International Atomic Energy Agency

text_trans: If you don't understand， don't mess around. Fukushima's first cooling water system is involved in cooling the radiation heat released by the core nuclear fuel rods of the nuclear power plant. It directly experiences high tritium concentration and contains radioactive heavy elements. Qinshan's second cooling water system is used to cool the first cooling water to maintain the thermal balance of the entire nuclear power plant. This cooling water does not enter the nuclear radiation zone and does not intersect with the first cooling water. There is almost no radioactivity

text_trans: Japan's discharge is not nuclear wastewater， but rather nuclear wastewater. The concept of cooling water that has passed through the core of a nuclear reactor and cooling water that has not passed through the core are different. The former is called primary cooling water， while the latter is called secondary cooling water. Although it has not passed through the core， secondary cooling water also contains trace amounts of radioactivity. The main radioactive element is tritium， which can be directly discharged into the sea as long as it meets the safety standards of the International Atomic Energy Agency

text_trans: What is wrong with Japan? It is a mistake to falsely claim that nuclear wastewater is treated as nuclear wastewater. Every nuclear power plant has nuclear wastewater， which is only used for cooling treatment and does not come into contact with radioactive substances. After treatment， it can be discharged domestically， even if it is the same for all nuclear power plants in the world. What is nuclear wastewater? It is the water produced by the melting and cooling water of the core in Fukushima， which was directly in contact with radioactive substances， after the tsunami. This is the nuclear wastewater released by Japan. Now we can understand it

After treatment， it can be discharged domestically， even if it is the same for all nuclear power plants in the world. What is nuclear wastewater? It is the water produced by the melting and cooling water of the core in Fukushima， which was directly in contact with radioactive substances， after the tsunami. This is the nuclear wastewater released by Japan. Now we can understand it
